description: This native species are about 7-9 inches long with spiny, rough scales along their backs. This was a male lizard due to its beautiful underbelly which is typically brighter during mating season. These lizards have incredible climbing abilities often running up the nearest tree as we walk by. These desert spiny lizards are not aggressive towards humans and will typically be seen basking in the sun on a warm day!

description: Gopher snakes are non-venomous, constrictor snakes and are often mistaken as rattlesnakes due to their color and pattern! They are diurnal and can often be seen active during the day except in the hotter months here. Not only do they look similar to rattlesnakes, but they also scare off predators by quickly moving their bodies creating a rattle-like sound, can be heard hissing loudly and can even flatten their heads similar to that of a western diamondback. To catch their prey (rodents, mice, ground squirrels, birds, eggs & lizards) they have the ability to construct and suffocate them and can dislocate their jaws to consume larger mammals. Wild! I’ve seen several of these snakes recently in the cooler months and hope that residents of this area can spot the difference between them and rattlesnakes!!
